# UniPilot Security

Security correctness is part of the backend grade. Treat every item below as mandatory.

## Authentication (JWT)
- Use JWT for all authentication. Issue tokens on login/register only.
- Sign tokens with a strong secret loaded from an environment variable (e.g. `JWT_SECRET`). Never hardcode it.
- Set a sensible expiry (e.g. access token 15m–1h). Reject expired or malformed tokens.
- Verify the token signature and claims on every protected request via middleware.
- Return `401 Unauthorized` for missing/invalid tokens, `403 Forbidden` for valid tokens lacking permission.

## Passwords (bcrypt)
- NEVER store passwords in plain text anywhere (DB, logs, responses, error messages).
- Hash all passwords with bcrypt (cost factor >= 10) before persisting.
- Compare passwords using bcrypt's constant-time compare. Never compare hashes manually.
- Never return password hashes in any API response.

## Protected Endpoints
- All student-specific endpoints MUST require a valid JWT.
- Enforce ownership/authorization: a student may only read/modify their own data. Check the user id from the token against the requested resource.
- Apply auth middleware at the router level so no protected route is accidentally left open.

## Input Validation
- Validate ALL request bodies, params, and query strings at the boundary before processing.
- Use schema-based validation (e.g. Zod / Joi / Pydantic depending on stack). Reject unknown fields.
- Fail fast with `400 Bad Request` and a clear, non-leaky message.
- Never trust external data, including AI service responses.

## Rate Limiting
- Apply rate limiting to all authentication endpoints (login, register, token refresh).
- Apply rate limiting to all AI endpoints to prevent abuse and cost overrun.
- Prefer a shared store (Redis) so limits hold across replicas.
- Return `429 Too Many Requests` when limits are exceeded.

## Secrets & Error Handling
- Load all secrets (JWT secret, DB URI, AI keys) from environment variables. Provide a `.env.example`.
- Validate that required secrets are present at startup; fail fast if missing.
- Error messages must not leak stack traces, secrets, or internal details to clients.
- Before any commit, verify no secrets are committed.

## Network Exposure
- Only the API/web container may be exposed to clients.
- MongoDB, Redis, the worker, and the AI service must stay on the internal Docker network only.
